---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { isBlogPublished } from '../../lib/blogGate';
import BlogCrossLinks from '../../components/BlogCrossLinks.astro';

const slug = Astro.url.pathname.replace('/blog/', '').replace(/\/$/, '');
const isPublished = await isBlogPublished(slug);
if (!isPublished) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---

<Layout title="Why Engineers Use Millimeters Instead of Centimeters" description="Why engineers use millimeters instead of centimeters. Precision, convention, and how mm reduces errors in technical work." keywords="millimeters engineering, mm vs cm, technical drawings units, engineering measurements, metric precision, CAD units, mechanical engineering mm">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Length</span>
      </nav>
      <BlogCrossLinks title="Why Engineers Use Millimeters Instead of Centimeters" />
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 16, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>If you have ever looked at an engineering drawing, you will notice all dimensions are in millimeters — not centimeters, not meters, not inches. A bracket might be labelled "45.5" without any unit, and everyone in the field knows it means 45.5 mm. Why is this the convention?</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">The Practical Reasons</h2>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Whole numbers for most parts:</strong> Most manufactured parts have dimensions between 1 and 1000 mm. Using mm means you rarely need decimal points for standard tolerance work (a 25 mm bolt, not 2.5 cm or 0.025 m)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Eliminates decimal confusion:</strong> Writing "2.5 cm" risks misreading the decimal as "25 cm" — a 10x error. Writing "25 mm" has no ambiguity</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>One unit throughout:</strong> When everything is in mm, you never mix up cm and m on the same drawing</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>International standard:</strong> ISO 129 and ISO 80000 specify mm as the preferred unit for engineering drawings</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">The Decimal Problem</h2>
      <p>Consider three ways to write the same dimension:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>0.0375 m — four decimal places, easy to misread</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>3.75 cm — requires a decimal point</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>37.5 mm — clean, readable, fewer digits</span>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>In a workshop environment with grease, poor lighting, and time pressure, the clearest notation wins. Millimeters give you whole numbers or simple one-decimal values for almost everything you would machine, print, or fabricate.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">When Precision Goes Further</h2>
      <p>For high-precision work, engineers use decimal millimeters:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Standard machining: ±0.1 mm tolerance</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Precision machining: ±0.01 mm tolerance</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Grinding/lapping: ±0.001 mm (1 micrometre)</span>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>Even at micrometre precision, it is written as 25.003 mm rather than switching to a different unit. Consistency reduces errors.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">What About Other Industries?</h2>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Architecture:</strong> Uses mm in metric countries (a wall might be 2400 mm tall)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Electronics:</strong> PCB design uses mm (component pads at 0.5 mm pitch)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>3D Printing:</strong> Slicers and CAD software default to mm</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Construction (US):</strong> Still uses feet, inches, and fractions (1/16")</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Aerospace:</strong> Often uses inches in the US, mm elsewhere</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Converting Between Units</h2>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>1 mm = 0.1 cm = 0.001 m</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>1 mm = 0.03937 inches</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>1 inch = 25.4 mm (exact)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>10 mm = 1 cm</span>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>The relationship between mm and inches is especially important because many legacy parts are still dimensioned in imperial. The exact conversion (25.4 mm per inch) makes dual-dimensioning straightforward.</p>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Try It Now</h3>
        <a href="/convert/length" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 text-white text-sm font-semibold hover:bg-amber-600 transition-colors">Open Length Converter →</a>
      </div>
    
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 p-4 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl">
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">🔗 Try our converter: <a href="/convert/length" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 font-bold hover:underline">Open Converter →</a></p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
